   
   (Message)
   
   
   Program state inspection and stack trace reading reveals that the program
   crashes during a loop with push_back calls on a vector. AddressSanitizer
   reports a use-after-free READ due to a dangling iterator.
   
   
   Assuming that we found the line in the code with the loop that is causing the
   crash, let's read the source code surrounding that line:
   
   
   
   
   We now see that the iterator is captured before the loop and used after the
   vector has been reallocated, causing the use-after-free.
   
   
   The local fix is to move the iterator after the loop:
   
   
   ```diff
   diff --git a/program.cpp b/program.cpp
   index 123456..789012 100644
   --- a/program.cpp
   +++ b/program.cpp
   @@ -10,7 +10,7 @@ int main() {
      for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        vec.push_back(i);
      }
   -  int& ref = vec[0];
   +  int& ref = vec.back();
      // use ref
    }
   ```
   
   However, a more thorough root-cause fix would be to use
   `std::vector::begin()` or `std::vector::front()` instead of capturing an
   iterator before the loop. This ensures that the iterator remains valid even
   after reallocations:
   
   
   ```cpp
   int main() {
     std::vector<int> vec;
     for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
       vec.push_back(i);
     }
     int& ref = vec.back();
     // use ref
   }
   ```
   
   
   GLOBAL FIX:
   Use iterators and references instead of capturing indices, especially in
   loops that may reallocate the underlying storage. This ensures that iterators
   and references remain valid and prevents use-after-free errors. Additionally,
   prefer `std::vector::begin()` and `std::vector::front()` over manual index
   calculations for guaranteed valid iterators.
